solution.p:
We will need to find a and b in the equation f(x)=a\,b^x. We begin by using the given ordered pairs to write a system 
        of equations

          7  & =  a\,b     
          53 & =  a\,b^{10} 

        We can eliminate a by equating the quotients formed by the two sides of the equations.

          \frac{53}{7} = \frac{a\,b^{10}}{a\,b}

        which simplifies to b^9=\frac{53}{7}. This means that 

          b = \left(\frac{53}{7}\right)^{\sfrac{1}{9}}

        If we substitute this 
        value of b into the first equation, we obtain

          a & = \frac{7}{b}
          & = \frac{7}{\left(\frac{53}{7}\right)^{\sfrac{1}{9}}}
          & = \frac{7^{\sfrac{10}{9}}}{53^{\sfrac{1}{9}}}    

        We conclude that 

          f(x) & = \frac{7^{\sfrac{10}{9}}}{53^{\sfrac{1}{9}}}\left(\frac{53}{7}\right)^{\sfrac{x}{9}}
          & = \frac{7^{\sfrac{10}{9}}}{53^{\sfrac{1}{9}}}\left(\left(\frac{53}{7}\right)^{\sfrac{1}{9}}\right)^x
          & \approx 5.59 (1.252237)^x

Since we are trying to use an exponential model, we are searching for values of a and b such that the curve y=a\,b^t will pass through these points. We need
25 & = a\,b^0 \\ 2391 & = a\,b^{7}
The first equation immediately tells us that a=25. Now the second equation reduces to
2391 {}={}25\,b^{7} & \Longrightarrow \frac{2391}{25} {}={} b^7 & \Longrightarrow b {}={} \left(\frac{2391}{25}\right)^{\sfrac17}
So we can model the number of infected people as a function of the number of days since the outbreak was first noticed using the model
f(t) & =25\left(\left(\frac{2391}{25}\right)^{\sfrac17}\right)^t & =25\left(\frac{2391}{25}\right)^{\sfrac{t}7}

image.latex-image-code:
\begin{tikzpicture}
\begin{axis}[
width=.3\textwidth,
xmin=-2,xmax=15,
ymin=-20,ymax=300,
xtick={2,4,...,14},
xlabel=<m>t</m>,
ytick={50,100,...,250},
yticklabels={5000,10000,15000,20000,25000}
]
\addplot expression[domain=-1:10.7]{.25*(2391/25)^(x/7)};
\addplot[soldot]coordinates{(0,.25)(7,23.91)};
\end{axis}
\end{tikzpicture}

statement.p:
          Each fish  costs 10 coins and sells for 15 coins after 1 day (because of its larger size). 
          Given that  we start with 20 coins
          on day 0, the transactions for the  first 3 days will be as follows:


 on day 0 we buy 2 fish;

 on day 1 we sell both fish for a total of 30 coins, and then buy 3 fish;

on day 2 we sell our 3 fish for a total of 45 coins,and then buy 4 fish; 

we have 5 coins remaining as we cannot have fractions of fish.

